Even with all the other sports that it has, however, WBD=E2=80=99s executiv=
es cannot be Pollyannaish about this turn of events. Historically, company =
executives have believed that the distributors valued the NBA far more than=
 the other sports=E2=80=94and paid for it=E2=80=94because they did. =E2=80=
=9CThe working assumption for the people who are at Turner, and the old Tim=
e Warner analysts like myself, was that the NBA was a key feature of
their negotiating clout,=E2=80=9D Nathanson said.

Nathanson even hypothesized that Comcast may be playing four-dimensional ch=
ess=E2=80=94outbidding WBD for the NBA so that they can eventually save som=
e money in distribution fees to carry its pay TV networks on their cable sy=
stems. Still, the financial community is concerned that WBD=E2=80=99s pay T=
V relationships will suffer if they lose the NBA. =E2=80=9CDoes Comcast hav=
e a deeper motive here?=E2=80=9D Nathanson asked.

This is one area where Zaslav has a ton of experience, of course. Before he=
 stepped into his role as a media mogul, Zaslav spent his days mired in Exc=
el spreadsheets, heading up NBC=E2=80=99s cable and satellite relationships=
=2E Dick Ebersol has credited Zaz with=20=
convincing cable and satellite compani=
es to pay a surcharge for NBC=E2=80=99s channels back in the 1990s as a way=
 to help NBC afford Olympic rights.

But Nathanson also dismissed the idea that Zaslav would be able to use any =
money saved to buy more rights.
UFC rights are up next year, sure, and ESPN seems likely to exercise an out=
 in its MLB deal. But most rights fees=E2=80=94including the highly rated N=
FL and college football=E2=80=94are tied up into the next decade. =E2=80=9C=
If they walk from the NBA, TNT is going to miss six weeks of playoffs that =
drive some of cable=E2=80=99s biggest audiences. That's really where the he=
at is,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CI don't know what they can do to repla=
ce those six weeks. There's not a lot you can do right now, except pick up =
some sports rights around the edges and negotiate when the distributors=E2=
=80=99 bills come due.=E2=80=9D

When I asked Greenfield what advice he=E2=80=99d give Zaslav, he suggested =
cutting sports on streaming to protect the distribution relationships as mu=
ch as possible. =E2=80=9CMaking it so that you could get the NHL, NASCAR, a=
nd college football on Max only puts them in a more precarious position,=E2=
=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThey should be doing everything humanly possible t=
o protect their distribution relationship.=E2=80=9D

Indeed, Zaz is doing the opposite by leaning into Venu and building out the=
 Bleacher Report package. Greenfield also said that he would make the UFC, =
whose deal with ESPN ends next year, his number one focus. =E2=80=9CUFC=E2=
=80=99s pay-per-views could work well for WBD,=E2=80=9D Greenfield said. =
=E2=80=9CThe transactional model of pay-per-view works very nicely with how=
 Max is set up, and it's not competitive with the bundle.=E2=80=9D

From the Cheap Seats

On NBA media rights (what else?): =E2=80=9CI think two forces are driving h=
igh bids: legacy mediacos need the NBA to support affiliate fees funding tr=
ansition to some unknown future state, and streamers (AMZN) building a gian=
t pool of rights to ultimately ladder up to a main NFL package (bonus that =
NBA is popular globally). Amazon has been methodical in building its rights=
 up. A marquee NBA package means fans probably watch two games a week durin=
g late fall/winter (NFL Thurs). My guess is that over the next few years, M=
LB ends up on Amazon, as well=E2=80=94all of this with an eye towards a mai=
n NFL package in the future. When the next NFL contract comes due, there wi=
ll be ~50-55M pay TV households at best. Fox/Paramount are going to be in t=
he same position as WBD today with the NBA, existential to win, but unable =
to afford it. This NBA deal was basically
a test run, but also a ladder, to the endgame. =E2=80=94 @modestproposal1 (=
 https://x.com/modestproposal1/status/1795518337243582957?utm_campaign=3DTh=
e+Varsity+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F30%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Varsity+-+SUBSC=
RIBERS+%285%2F6%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )on X

More NBA media rights talk: =E2=80=9CEnjoyed your appearance on the Plain E=
nglish pod with Derek Thompson. A few thoughts from an ad buyer=E2=80=99s p=
erspective:
1) Citing declining Nielsen ratings needs more context. Namely that Nielsen=
 critics say they undercount young and diverse audiences, both of which are=
 an important part of the NBA audience. We use Nielsen ratings as a proxy f=
or success of an advertisement placement, based on how many people saw it. =
The real measure of success is: Did the placement drive an advertiser=E2=80=
=99s business? Advertisers and agencies are better than ever at understandi=
ng which ad
placements work. Advertisers have a high demand for NBA because it works to=
 drive sales, clicks, branding, etcetera.
2) The Nielsen ratings do not count the streaming audience. While not massi=
ve, it=E2=80=99s easily 5 percent incremental audience. If entertainment pr=
ogramming is declining >15 percent each year and the NBA is relatively flat=
, the gap between everything else and the NBA is wider than ever and makes =
the NBA (and other sports) even more valuable.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94Horizon Me=
dia chief investment officer David Campanelli via X ( https://x.com/DavidCa=
mpHrzn/status/1795659132206534795?utm_campaign=3DThe+Varsity+-+SUBSCRIBERS+=
%285%2F30%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Varsity+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%285%2F6%2F24%29&=
utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42a=
bd12a )

Still more NBA media rights talk: =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s possible that the n=
umber NBC ultimately pays will prove to be an overpay for an NBA B package.=
 It=E2=80=99s definitely being
portrayed as NBC winning and WBD losing and nobody is really questioning th=
e wisdom of the NBC number.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A network executive

Everyone=E2=80=99s a critic: =E2=80=9COmg=E2=80=A6 I'm canceling ... You ar=
e too arrogant. R.I.P. Bill Walton.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A marketing consultan=
t

Back on Monday,
John

