          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Zaslav put on a bra=
ve face at today=E2=80=99s Bernstein conference, hyping WBD=E2=80=99s other=
 sports assets: March Madness, MLB playoffs, NHL playoffs (including the St=
anley Cup Finals every other year), NASCAR, College Football Playoffs, and =
U.S. soccer. WBD, it would seem, has enough popular sports to prevent cable=
 and satellite operators from dropping them in the immediate future, or cut=
ting their payouts to WBD significantly. <br/><br/>Even with all the other =
sports that it has, however, WBD=E2=80=99s executives cannot be Pollyannais=
h about this turn of events. Historically, company executives have believed=
 that the distributors valued the NBA far more than the other sports=E2=80=
=94and paid for it=E2=80=94because <i>they did</i>. =E2=80=9CThe working as=
sumption for the people who are at Turner, and the old Time Warner analysts=
 like myself, was that the NBA was a key feature of
their negotiating clout,=E2=80=9D Nathanson said.<br/><br/>Nathanson even h=
ypothesized that Comcast may be playing four-dimensional chess=E2=80=94outb=
idding WBD for the NBA so that they can eventually save some money in distr=
ibution fees to carry its pay TV networks on their cable systems. Still, th=
e financial community is concerned that WBD=E2=80=99s pay TV relationships =
will suffer if they lose the NBA. =E2=80=9CDoes Comcast have a deeper motiv=
e here?=E2=80=9D Nathanson asked. <br/><br/>This is one area where Zaslav h=
as a ton of experience, of course. Before he stepped into his role as a med=
ia mogul, Zaslav spent his days mired in Excel spreadsheets, heading up NBC=
=E2=80=99s cable and satellite relationships. <b>Dick Ebersol</b> has credi=
ted Zaz with convincing cable and satellite companies to pay a surcharge fo=
r NBC=E2=80=99s channels back in the 1990s as a way to help NBC afford Olym=
pic rights. <br/><br/>But Nathanson also dismissed the idea that Zaslav wou=
ld be able to use any money saved to buy more rights.
UFC rights are up next year, sure, and ESPN seems likely to exercise an out=
 in its MLB deal. But most rights fees=E2=80=94including the highly rated N=
FL and college football=E2=80=94are tied up into the next decade. =E2=80=9C=
If they walk from the NBA, TNT is going to miss six weeks of playoffs that =
drive some of cable=E2=80=99s biggest audiences. That&#39;s really where th=
e heat is,=E2=80=9D he told me. =E2=80=9CI don&#39;t know what they can do =
to replace those six weeks. There&#39;s not a lot you can do right now, exc=
ept pick up some sports rights around the edges and negotiate when the dist=
ributors=E2=80=99 bills come due.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>When I asked Greenfield=
 what advice he=E2=80=99d give Zaslav, he suggested cutting sports on strea=
ming to protect the distribution relationships as much as possible. =E2=80=
=9CMaking it so that you could get the NHL, NASCAR, and college football on=
 Max only puts them in a more precarious position,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=
=9CThey should be doing everything humanly possible to protect their distri=
bution relationship.=E2=80=9D
<br/><br/>Indeed, Zaz is doing the opposite by leaning into Venu and buildi=
ng out the Bleacher Report package. Greenfield also said that he would make=
 the UFC, whose deal with ESPN ends next year, his number one focus. =E2=80=
=9CUFC=E2=80=99s pay-per-views could work well for WBD,=E2=80=9D Greenfield=
 said. =E2=80=9CThe transactional model of pay-per-view works very nicely w=
ith how Max is set up, and it&#39;s not competitive with the bundle.=E2=80=
=9D<br/></td>
         </tr>
